Watercolors by Alvaro Castagnet

 Alvaro Castagnet (born in Montevideo, Uruguay) is an inspirational and expressive watercolor...
posts.caption:
crossconnectmag:

Watercolors by Alvaro Castagnet

Alvaro Castagnet (born in Montevideo, Uruguay) is an inspirational and expressive watercolor painter who has won many prestigious international awards, travels extensively, exhibiting, judging, and teaching the arts of watercolor. He is a member of many art societies, including AWI, and AWS. He is a successful author, who holds highly popular workshops and his works are collected worldwide. Check out his website.

 "A painting only exists when you capture the deepest facet of the subject.“ 

Art is the only way to run away without leaving home - run with us.

posted by tu recepcja

posts.summary: HEIDI ANNALISE ART - I didn't study art in school, and I took a winding path to get here, but... So I decided to leave my...
posts.caption:
HEIDI ANNALISE ART - I didn’t study art in school, and I took a winding path to get here, but…
So I decided to leave my respectable 9-to-5 job on the East Coast in 2015 to become an artist. I wasn’t even entirely sure what I wanted to paint, but I was pretty sure that inspiration could be found in my magnificent home state of Colorado, so I moved back. All my recent paintings reflect the joy of being once again surrounded by the beauty of the mountains. Floating between realism and impressionism, my artwork adds an element of fantasy to the natural world with heightened colors and simplified shapes. By bringing glimpses of nature into our indoor environments, we can soak up these extraordinary vistas on all of our more ordinary days, and remind ourselves to go exploring whenever we can.

Check us out on Instagram: @Lesstalkmoreillustration

posts.summary: B O W L I N G    A L L E Y S Photographer ROBERT GÖTZFRIED - For a couple of years I've been trying to find the most exciting...
posts.caption:
B O W L I N G    A L L E Y S
Photographer ROBERT GÖTZFRIED - For a couple of years I’ve been trying to find the most exciting bowling alleys and “Kegelbahnen” in Southern Germany. Kegeln is pretty similar to bowling but with only nine pins, smaller balls, and shorter lanes. It used to be a big thing in Germany in the 60’s, 70’s and 80’s. These days thsi sport is not en vogue anymore and it seems that mostly older people go these “Kegelbahnen”.

posts.summary: Architect IRAKLI KALANDARISHVILI - While projecting a facade we tried to see the typical historical details of Old Tbilisi,...
posts.caption:
Architect IRAKLI KALANDARISHVILI - While projecting a facade we tried to see the typical historical details of Old Tbilisi, which define an architectural value of Old Tbilisi up to this date.

In our project there are presented the highly artistic works of houses with yards and balconies, which are located in Old Tbilisi. These works are made by wooden ornaments. It creates a pleasant visual area and it is a part of an interior at the same time.

A square, which is in front of the main entrance of the building we present as an indivisible part of the facade and the hotel by using the display space for selected sculptor’s seasonal exhibition. The sculptures will be relevant to season and the square or an area.

posts.summary: MONOLOG AUS DEM 11TEN STOCK With ALICJA KWADE we enter the field of artistic research of the sciences. The exhibition...
posts.caption:
MONOLOG AUS DEM 11TEN STOCK
With ALICJA KWADE we enter the field of artistic research of the sciences. The exhibition demonstrates both the consistency and the versatility that have marked the sculptor and conceptual artist’s treatment of the seemingly predictable and yet unimaginable for more than ten years. She starts from the basic questions of theoretical physics, philosophy and sociology: How did the universe originate? Are there parallel worlds? What is time? What is reality? What is delusion? What is truth? From this starting point the Polish-born, Berlin-based artist poses fundamental questions to the norms and models of our everyday social life. With extreme precision, simple means and a great sense of the contingent and the paradoxical she succeeds in translating complex correlations to sculpture.

posts.summary: HAPPY ACCIDENTS In this ongoing series of works by artist Joe Suzuki, pools of paint appear like maniacal smiles as they drip...
posts.caption:
HAPPY ACCIDENTS

In this ongoing series of works by artist Joe Suzuki, pools of paint appear like maniacal smiles as they drip from cans and bottles.

“I consider my work to be artifacts of my own particular culture, which is not the generalized Japanese American culture, but that which formed as a direct result of being a first generation immigrant,” Suzuki shares in an artist statement. “Through a long assimilation process, I found myself not fully belonging to either culture, but rather somewhere in between, which I began to call Japamerica.”

posts.summary: BLANK Artist MARINA GONZALEZ EME - ‘Blank’ is an adjective, it is a state of mind, a deep feeling, an unfilled gap. I start to...
posts.caption:
BLANK
Artist MARINA GONZALEZ EME - ‘Blank’ is an adjective, it is a state of mind, a deep feeling, an unfilled gap. I start to paint in a blank space. My mind is blank. The surface of the canvas is an empty place where I lose (and find) myself everyday. A place where my ideas break up into many eyes, hands, colours and lines.
